 PM ET","published":"2015-08-01 13:02:54","updated":"2015-08-01 17:02:54","minute":"1:02 pm","short":"1:02 PM ET"},"authors":[{"id":193865,"url":"http:\/\/time.com\/author\/associated-press\/","name":"Yuri Kageyama\/AP","bio":"","short_bio":"","types":[],"twitter":"","twitter_url":"","gplus":"","fb":"","email":"","thumbnail":null,"contributor":false,"search_link":false}],"content":"<p>(TOKYO)&mdash;The head of the failed Japan-based bitcoin exchange Mt. Gox was arrested in Tokyo on Saturday on suspicion of inflating his cash account by $1 million, authorities said.<\/p>\n<p>Mark Karpeles, 30, is suspected of accessing the exchange&#8217;s computer system in February 2013 and inflating his account, Japanese police said. If found guilty, the France-born Karpeles could face up to five years in prison, or a fine of up to 500,000 yen ($4,000).<\/p>\n<p>Karpeles&#8217; lawyer said his client denies wrongdoing, the Kyodo News agency reported.<\/p>\n<p>Mt. Gox went offline early last year. Karpeles said then that tens of thousands of bitcoins worth several hundred million dollars were unaccounted for, and suggested they were stolen by hacking.<\/p>\n<p>The relationship between the lost bitcoins and the inflated account was not immediately clear.<\/p>\n<p>Japanese TV showed a T-shirt-clad Karpeles, with a baseball cap pulled low over his face, being led into a police car from his home in Tokyo.<\/p>\n<div class=\"video-wrapper brightcove-size-large\" data-pos=\"6\" data-continuous=\"1\" data-playlist=\"0\"><object id=\"bc-video-2804786912001-6\" class=\"BrightcoveExperience\"><param name=\"bgcolor\" value=\"#000000\"><param name=\"width\" value=\"100%\"><param name=\"height\" value=\"100%\"><param name=\"playerID\" value=\"1847503743001\"><param name=\"isVid\" value=\"true\"><param name=\"isUI\" value=\"true\"><param name=\"dynamicStreaming\" value=\"true\"><param name=\"videoSmoothing\" value=\"true\"><param name=\"linkBaseURL\" value=\"http:\/\/ti.me\/1IBTuH5\"><param name=\"includeAPI\" value=\"true\"><param name=\"templateLoadHandler\" value=\"Time.application.brightcoveFacade._onTemplateLoad\"><param name=\"templateReadyHandler\" value=\"Time.application.brightcoveFacade._onTemplateReady\"><param name=\"wmode\" value=\"opaque\"><param name=\"htmlFallback\" value=\"true\"><param name=\"@videoPlayer\" value=\"2804786912001\"><\/object><\/div>\n<p>Japanese authorities have acknowledged they were baffled by the Mt. Gox case because they had never dealt with possible crime dealing with bitcoin. Experts also said it might be difficult to take action because of the absence of laws over virtual currencies.<\/p>\n<p>The bitcoin community worldwide has been outraged by Mt. Gox&#8217;s apparent incompetence.<\/p>\n<p>The Mt. Gox debacle served to highlight the perils of bitcoin transactions. Bitcoins are not regulated by central banks or other financial authorities. Bitcoin proponents have long said Mt. Gox is just an exception.<\/p>\n<p>Legislation is in the works in California, for instance, to regulate businesses that hold bitcoin and other virtual currency in a way similar to banks. New York has also issued rules overseeing bitcoin.<\/p>\n","read_more":true,"section":{"name":"World","slug":"world","url":"http:\/\/time.com\/world\/","description":"The latest news and analysis from TIME's correspondents on world politics, diplomacy, conflict, culture, humanitarian disasters, religion and much more","world":true},"tag":{"name":"Japan","slug":"japan","url":"http:\/\/time.com\/tag\/japan\/"},"tags":"Japan","hero":{"class":"portrait","thumbnail":"https:\/\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2015\/08\/mark-karpeles.jpg?quality=65&strip=color&w=100&h=100&crop=1","src":{"small":"https:\/\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2015\/08\/mark-karpeles.jpg?quality=65&strip=color&w=280","small_2x":"https:\/\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2015\/08\/mark-karpeles.jpg?quality=65&strip=color&w=560","large":"https:\/\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2015\/08\/mark-karpeles.jpg?quality=65&strip=color&w=407","large_2x":"https:\/\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2015\/08\/mark-karpeles.jpg?quality=65&strip=color&w=814"},"credit":"Yuya Shino\u2014Reuters","caption":"Mark Karpeles, chief executive of Mt. Gox, attends a news conference at the Tokyo District Court on Feb. 28, 2014. ","alt":"Mark Karpeles Mt. Gox bitcoin","providers":[],"masonry":{"small_width":300,"small_height":359,"large_width":625,"large_height":748}},"id":3981203,"encoded_url":"http%3A%2F%2Ftime.com%2F3981203%2Fmt-gox-bitcoin-mark-karpeles-arrest%2F","encoded_shortlink":"http%3A%2F%2Fti.me%2F1IBTuH5","encoded_title":"Leader+of+Mt.+Gox+Bitcoin+Exchange+Arrested+in+Tokyo","twitter_text":"Leader%20of%20Mt.%20Gox%20Bitcoin%20exchange%20arrested%20in%20Tokyo","twitter_via":"TIMEWorld","social_encoded_url":{"facebook":"http%3A%2F%2Ftime.com%2F3981203%2Fmt-gox-bitcoin-mark-karpeles-arrest%2F%3Fxid%3Dfbshare","twitter":"http%3A%2F%2Fti.me%2F1IfMlZp","linkedin":"http%3A%2F%2Ftime.com%2F3981203%2Fmt-gox-bitcoin-mark-karpeles-arrest%2F%3Fxid%3Dlinkedinshare","google":"http%3A%2F%2Ftime.com%2F3981203%2Fmt-gox-bitcoin-mark-karpeles-arrest%2F%3Fxid%3Dgplusshare","whatsapp":"Leader%20of%20Mt.%20Gox%20Bitcoin%20exchange%20arrested%20in%20Tokyo%0Ahttp%3A%2F%2Ftime.com%2F3981203%2Fmt-gox-bitcoin-mark-karpeles-arrest%2F%3Fxid%3Dwhatsappshare"},"ads":{"neg":"false","post_title":"Leader of Mt. Gox Bitcoin Exchange Arrested in Tokyo"},"email_title":"Leader%20of%20Mt.%20Gox%20Bitcoin%20Exchange%20Arrested%20in%20Tokyo%20%7C%20TIME","email_body":"Leader%20of%20Mt.%20Gox%20Bitcoin%20Exchange%20Arrested%20in%20Tokyo%0A%0AMark%20Karpeles%2C%2030%2C%20could%20face%20up%20to%20five%20years%20in%20prison%0A%0Ahttp%3A%2F%2Ftime.com%2F3981203%2Fmt-gox-bitcoin-mark-karpeles-arrest%2F%3Fxid%3Demailshare","omniture":{"modules":"[time-rail-ad]"},"outbrain":{"url":"http:\/\/time.com\/3981203\/mt-gox-bitcoin-mark-karpeles-arrest\/","desktop_widget_id":"AR_6","mobile_widget_id":"MB_1","widget_id":"AR_6"},"classes":"metered","article_tile_thumbnail":"https:\/\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2015\/08\/mark-karpeles.jpg?quality=65&strip=color&w=74&h=74&crop=1"},{"url":"http:\/\/time.com\/3980583\/student-debt-crisis\/","shortlink":"http:\/\/ti.me\/1DfLue5","title":"Taking Aim at Student Debt","friendly_title":"Taking Aim at Student Debt","post_type":"post","available":true,"time_article":true,"comments_allowed":true,"show_comments":true,"short_title":"Taking Aim at Student Debt","contributor":true,"excerpt":"We need a long-term solution that tackles both education and wealth inequality in today's society","format":"article","time":{"pretty":"12:30 PM ET","published":"2015-08-01 12:30:52","updated":"2015-08-01 16:30:52","minute":"12:30 pm","short":"12:30 PM ET"},"authors":[{"id":65301,"url":"http:\/\/time.com\/author\/new-america-foundation\/","name":"P.R. Lockhart \/ New America","bio":"","short_bio":"","types":["contributor"],"twitter":"","twitter_url":"","gplus":"","fb":"","email":"","thumbnail":null,"contributor":true,"search_link":false}],"content":"<p class=\"normal\">When the class of 2015 graduated in May, they took more than a diploma and happy memories away from campus. They also left with an average student debt of $35,000 for a bachelor&rsquo;s degree&mdash;earning the distinction of being the <a href=\"http:\/\/blogs.wsj.com\/economics\/2015\/05\/08\/congratulations-class-of-2015-youre-the-most-indebted-ever-for-now\/\"><span style=\"color:#1155cc;\">most indebted graduating class in history<\/span><\/a>. Unfortunately, it&rsquo;s a title they will probably concede to the class of 2016 next spring.<\/p>\n<p class=\"normal\">With numbers like these, it is becoming clear that innovative approaches are desperately needed. With their new book, The Real College Debt Crisis: How Student Borrowing Threatens Financial Well-Being and Erodes the American Dream, University of Kansas professors William Elliott III and Melinda Lewis offer one such paradigm shift. They argue that we&rsquo;re missing the bigger picture when it comes to student debt. The skyrocketing rates of student indebtedness are, in their estimation, a symptom of an even more serious problem: that the reluctant acceptance of debt as a de facto method for paying for college <a href=\"http:\/\/www.washingtonpost.com\/news\/wonkblog\/wp\/2015\/07\/29\/millennials-should-no-longer-dream-of-ever-becoming-millionaires\/\"><span style=\"color:#1155cc;\">reinforces social and financial inequality<\/span><\/a> by saddling borrowers with excessive financial burdens at the beginning of their careers and hurting their chances to achieve economic mobility post-graduation.<\/p>\n<p class=\"normal\">&ldquo;If we begin to think of education as a part of the economic mobility system, then we can begin to think of education&rsquo;s implications for children long after school,&rdquo; Elliott, who also serves as the founding director of the Center on Assets, Education, and Inclusion (AEDI), explained at a recent New America event. Along with his co-author, Elliott was joined by Demos Senior Policy Analyst Mark Huelsman and New America Education Policy Program Director Kevin Carey for a discussion on the importance of developing new college financing models that could reduce inequity between students of varying income levels.<\/p>\n<p class=\"normal\">&ldquo;We fundamentally believe that education is really important, but because of the weight of [student] debt, experts are starting to question whether or not the return on investment is really there,&rdquo; Elliott said.<\/p>\n<p class=\"normal\">The panelists&rsquo; conversation comes at a moment of heightened attention on the burdens student debt often places on young borrowers and their families. Last year, <a href=\"http:\/\/blogs.wsj.com\/washwire\/2014\/11\/13\/how-democrats-owe-their-midterm-losses-to-student-loans\/\"><span style=\"color:#1155cc;\">exit polling of Millennial voters<\/span><\/a> intimated that student debt was a point of concern during the midterm elections, prompting politicians to jump on an<span style=\"color:#1155cc;\"><a href=\"http:\/\/www.marketwatch.com\/story\/where-the-presidential-candidates-stand-on-student-debt-2015-07-28?siteid=rss&amp;rss=1\"> increasingly crowded &ldquo;student debt is a serious issue&#8221; bandwagon<\/a> <\/span>during the preliminary rounds of the 2016 presidential campaign. And in March, President Obama announced the creation of a <a href=\"https:\/\/www.whitehouse.gov\/blog\/2015\/03\/10\/student-aid-bill-rights-enhancing-protections-student-loan-borrowers\"><span style=\"color:#1155cc;\">Student Aid Bill of Rights<\/span><\/a> that seeks to change how federal agencies interact with students that take out federal loans to finance the cost of higher education.<\/p>\n<p class=\"normal\">Unfortunately, according to the panelists, <a href=\"http:\/\/www.washingtonpost.com\/business\/economy\/how-student-debt-became-a-presidential-campaign-issue\/2015\/05\/24\/1463948e-f41c-11e4-b2f3-af5479e6bbdd_story.html\"><span style=\"color:#1155cc;\">political discussions of the student debt crisis<\/span><\/a> often fail to acknowledge how student debt can have <a href=\"http:\/\/www.theatlantic.com\/business\/archive\/2013\/05\/how-colleges-are-selling-out-the-poor-to-court-the-rich\/275725\/\"><span style=\"color:#1155cc;\">disparate and lifelong<\/span><\/a> effects on the asset building capacity of young borrowers from different racial and economic backgrounds. It is often the students who stand to benefit the most from attending college who struggle with debt after graduation or drop out before receiving a degree, creating what Huelsman referred to as a &ldquo;<a href=\"http:\/\/www.demos.org\/publication\/debt-divide-racial-and-class-bias-behind-new-normal-student-borrowing\"><span style=\"color:#1155cc;\">Debt Divide<\/span><\/a>&rdquo;&mdash;a phenomenon wherein those with the highest need for student loans are the most susceptible to negative outcomes before and after graduation.<\/p>\n<p class=\"normal\">&ldquo;There is a fundamental difference in student debt that&rsquo;s taken on by someone from a low-income background and debt that&rsquo;s taken on by someone from a middle or upper class background,&rdquo; Huelsman said. &ldquo;There are people for whom every dollar matters so much more, and they don&rsquo;t have the extended family resources that can leverage assets to take on debt.&rdquo;<\/p><div class=\"content-ad\" id=\"content-ad-3980583\"><\/div>\n<p class=\"normal\">When speaking about the increase in the number of students taking out loans, Huelsman pointed out that the higher education system was never meant to trade debt for diplomas, but because of a series of policy changes that reduced institutional funding and increased costs, &ldquo;we now have an almost entirely debt-funded higher education system.&rdquo; And while media outlets and pundits are quick to highlight how <a href=\"http:\/\/www.bloomberg.com\/news\/articles\/2015-04-30\/how-student-loans-could-cripple-the-u-s-economy\"><span style=\"color:#1155cc;\">this debt-funded system is wreaking havoc on the economy<\/span><\/a>, Huelsman also noted that looking at the problem as being one of borrowers breaching <span style=\"color:#1155cc;\"><a href=\"http:\/\/blog.credit.com\/2013\/05\/student-loan-debt-how-much-is-too-much-66165\/?utm_source=MoneyMagazine&amp;utm_medium=content&amp;utm_content=IB_3&amp;utm_campaign=inequality_stats\">some invisible threshold of acceptable debt<\/a> <\/span>obscures a far more pressing question: why is debt even necessary to afford higher education in the first place?<\/p>\n<p class=\"normal\">Huelsman&rsquo;s comments resonated with a key argument Elliott and Lewis make in The Real College Debt Crisis&mdash;that despite the seemingly good intentions of policy wonks and reporters there is a disconnect between the aspects of the student debt &ldquo;crisis&rdquo; that are being addressed publicly and the challenges that are actually impacting the ability of borrowers to build assets and attain mobility. &ldquo;One of the problems that we get into when we aren&rsquo;t correctly diagnosing or defining the problems created by student debt is that the solutions we propose are not aimed at the right target,&rdquo; Lewis explained.<\/p>\n<p class=\"normal\">In their book, Elliott and Lewis advocate moving college financing away from a &ldquo;debt-dependency&rdquo; model (and the short-term solutions that it encourages) and towards an asset-building model that enables anyone willing to put in the effort to grow their wealth over time. One concrete mechanism they recommend is the increased use of Children&rsquo;s Savings Accounts (CSAs), as a tool for leveraging assets accumulated from birth as a form of financial aid. &ldquo;There is everything right with a centralized, portable financial product that will get more people to and through college,&rdquo; Huelsman noted when speaking of the CSA concept. &ldquo;But it has to mean something in the terms of college cost.&rdquo;<\/p>\n<p class=\"normal\">Carey agreed college cost is unlikely to decrease with the institutions themselves in the driver&rsquo;s seat, serving&mdash;as he put it&mdash;as both the benefactor and the perpetuator of the student debt crisis. &ldquo;It&rsquo;s pretty good to be in a business where your customers say to themselves &lsquo;Well if I gotta borrow, I gotta borrow,&rsquo;&rdquo; Carey said. &ldquo;Not many businesses have that luxury, but colleges and universities do.&rdquo; Carey also lamented the Obama administration&rsquo;s recent announcement that it <a href=\"http:\/\/www.washingtonpost.com\/news\/grade-point\/wp\/2015\/06\/25\/obama-administration-retreats-from-federal-college-rating-plan\/\"><span style=\"color:#1155cc;\">would abandon its plan to implement a college rating system<\/span><\/a>, which he felt had potential to help colleges take an active role in preventing their graduates from defaulting on their student loans.<\/p>\n<p class=\"normal\">Elliott acknowledged value in Carey&rsquo;s accountability-centric approach, but suggested that without an overhaul in how college educations are financed, the larger problem of student debt would remain.<\/p>\n<p class=\"normal\">&ldquo;We are afraid to re-envision and re-think how financial aid can be done,&rdquo; Elliott said. &ldquo;We need a long-term solution that not only changes education, but [also addresses] the great wealth inequality that we see in our society.&rdquo;<\/p>\n<p><em>This piece was originally published in New America&rsquo;s digital magazine, <\/em><em><a href=\"http:\/\/weeklywonk.newamerica.org\/\">The Weekly Wonk<\/a>. <\/em><em>Sign up to get it delivered to your inbox each Thursday <\/em><a href=\"http:\/\/weeklywonk.newamerica.net\/subscribe-email\/\"><em>here<\/em><\/a><em>, and <\/em><a href=\"https:\/\/twitter.com\/NewAmerica\"><em>follow @New America<\/em><\/a><em> on Twitter<br \/>\n<\/em><\/p>\n<p class=\"p1\"><div class=\"video-wrapper brightcove-size-large\" data-pos=\"8\" data-continuous=\"1\" data-playlist=\"0\"><object id=\"bc-video-4260687254001-8\" class=\"BrightcoveExperience\"><param name=\"bgcolor\" value=\"#000000\"><param name=\"width\" value=\"100%\"><param name=\"height\" value=\"100%\"><param name=\"playerID\" value=\"1847503743001\"><param name=\"isVid\" value=\"true\"><param name=\"isUI\" value=\"true\"><param name=\"dynamicStreaming\" value=\"true\"><param name=\"videoSmoothing\" value=\"true\"><param name=\"linkBaseURL\" value=\"http:\/\/ti.me\/1DfLue5\"><param name=\"includeAPI\" value=\"true\"><param name=\"templateLoadHandler\" value=\"Time.application.brightcoveFacade._onTemplateLoad\"><param name=\"templateReadyHandler\" value=\"Time.application.brightcoveFacade._onTemplateReady\"><param name=\"wmode\" value=\"opaque\"><param name=\"htmlFallback\" value=\"true\"><param name=\"@videoPlayer\" value=\"4260687254001\"><\/object><\/div><\/p>\n","read_more":true,"section":{"name":"Ideas","slug":"ideas","url":"http:\/\/time.com\/ideas\/","description":"TIME Ideas hosts the world's leading voices, providing commentary and expertise on the most compelling events in news, society, and culture. We welcome outside contributions. To submit a piece, email ideas@time.com.","ideas":true},"tag":{"name":"society","slug":"society","url":"http:\/\/time.com\/tag\/society\/"},"tags":"millennial|Money|society|student loan","hero":{"class":"portrait","thumbnail":"https:\/\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2015\/07\/graduation-cap-money-pile.jpg?quality=65&strip=color&w=100&h=100&crop=1","src":{"small":"https:\/\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2015\/07\/graduation-cap-money-pile.jpg?quality=65&strip=color&w=280","small_2x":"https:\/\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2015\/07\/graduation-cap-money-pile.jpg?quality=65&strip=color&w=334","large":"https:\/\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2015\/07\/graduation-cap-money-pile.jpg?quality=65&strip=color&w=334","large_2x":"https:\/\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2015\/07\/graduation-cap-money-pile.jpg?quality=65&strip=color&w=334"},"credit":"Getty Images","caption":"","alt":"graduation-cap-money-pile","providers":[],"masonry":{"small_width":300,"small_height":462,"large_width":625,"large_height":962}},"id":3980583,"encoded_url":"http%3A%2F%2Ftime.com%2F3980583%2Fstudent-debt-crisis%2F","encoded_shortlink":"http%3A%2F%2Fti.me%2F1DfLue5","encoded_title":"Taking+Aim+at+Student+Debt","twitter_text":"Taking%20aim%20at%20student%20debt","twitter_via":"TIMEIdeas","social_encoded_url":{"facebook":"http%3A%2F%2Ftime.com%2F3980583%2Fstudent-debt-crisis%2F%3Fxid%3Dfbshare","twitter":"http%3A%2F%2Fti.me%2F1KHWRLQ","linkedin":"http%3A%2F%2Ftime.com%2F3980583%2Fstudent-debt-crisis%2F%3Fxid%3Dlinkedinshare","google":"http%3A%2F%2Ftime.com%2F3980583%2Fstudent-debt-crisis%2F%3Fxid%3Dgplusshare","whatsapp":"Taking%20aim%20at%20student%20debt%0Ahttp%3A%2F%2Ftime.com%2F3980583%2Fstudent-debt-crisis%2F%3Fxid%3Dwhatsappshare"},"ads":{"neg":"false","post_title":"Taking Aim at Student Debt"},"Partner_Module":{"partner":"New America\/Weekly Wonk","post_title":"Taking Aim at Student Debt"},"email_title":"Taking%20Aim%20at%20Student%20Debt%20%7C%20TIME","email_body":"Taking%20Aim%20at%20Student%20Debt%0A%0AWe%20need%20a%20long-term%20solution%20that%20tackles%20both%20education%20and%20wealth%20inequality%20in%20today%27s%20society%0A%0Ahttp%3A%2F%2Ftime.com%2F3980583%2Fstudent-debt-crisis%2F%3Fxid%3Demailshare","omniture":{"modules":"[time-rail-ad]|[time-partner-module]|[time-magazine-module]|[outbrain-video-module]"},"outbrain":{"url":"http:\/\/time.com\/3980583\/student-debt-crisis\/","desktop_widget_id":"AR_6","mobile_widget_id":"MB_1","widget_id":"AR_6"},"classes":"metered","article_tile_thumbnail":"https:\/\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2015\/07\/graduation-cap-money-pile.jpg?quality=65&strip=color&w=74&h=74&crop=1"},{"url":"http:\/\/time.com\/3981194\/virus-sewage-olympics-rio-who\/","shortlink":"http:\/\/ti.me\/1IQoHbt","title":"WHO Seeks Virus Tests After Sewage Found in Rio&#8217;s Olympic Waters","friendly_title":"WHO Seeks Virus Tests After Sewage Found in Rio\u2019s Olympic Waters","post_type":"post","available":true,"time_article":true,"comments_allowed":true,"show_comments":true,"short_title":"WHO Seeks Virus Tests in Rio's Olympic Waters ","excerpt":"Officials are concerned about athletes' health","format":"brief","time":{"pretty":"12:23 PM ET","published":"2015-08-01 12:23:16","updated":"2015-08-01 16:23:16","minute":"12:23 pm","short":"12:23 PM ET"},"authors":[{"id":193865,"url":"http:\/\/time.com\/author\/associated-press\/","name":"Stephen Wade\/AP","bio":"","short_bio":"","types":[],"twitter":"","twitter_url":"","gplus":"","fb":"","email":"","thumbnail":null,"contributor":false,"search_link":false}],"content":"<p>(RIO DE JANEIRO) &mdash; The World Health Organization has asked the IOC to analyze virus levels in Rio de Janeiro&#8217;s Olympic waters, and the governing body of world sailing says it will start doing its own independent virus tests.<\/p>\n<p>The moves come after an Associated Press investigation showed a serious health risk to Olympic athletes in venues around Rio rife with sewage.<\/p>\n<p>In a statement to the AP, the World Health Organization said it suggested the International Olympic Committee start monitoring for viruses at the Rio venues.<\/p>\n<p>&#8220;WHO has also advised the IOC to widen the scientific base of indicators to include viruses,&#8221; the statement said. &#8220;The risk assessment should be revised accordingly, pending the results of further analysis. The Rio Local Organizing Committee and the IOC are requested to follow WHO recommendations on treatment of household and hospital waste.&#8221;<\/p>\n<p>A spokesman from the Rio organizing committee referred comment to the IOC, which is meeting in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia.<\/p>\n<p>Olympic organizers and the Brazilian government have tested only for bacteria to decide if the water is safe. Many experts say viruses are a far bigger problem and need to be monitored.<\/p>\n<p>The International Sailing Federation said independently it would start testing for viruses.<\/p>\n<p>&#8220;We&#8217;re going to find someone who can do the testing for us that can safely cover what we need to know from a virus perspective as well as the bacteria perspective,&#8221; Peter Sowrey, chief executive of the ISF, said. &#8220;That&#8217;s my plan.&#8221;<\/p>\n<div class=\"video-wrapper brightcove-size-large\" data-pos=\"10\" data-continuous=\"1\" data-playlist=\"0\"><object id=\"bc-video-4389502505001-10\" class=\"BrightcoveExperience\"><param name=\"bgcolor\" value=\"#000000\"><param name=\"width\" value=\"100%\"><param name=\"height\" value=\"100%\"><param name=\"playerID\" value=\"1847503743001\"><param name=\"isVid\" value=\"true\"><param name=\"isUI\" value=\"true\"><param name=\"dynamicStreaming\" value=\"true\"><param name=\"videoSmoothing\" value=\"true\"><param name=\"linkBaseURL\" value=\"http:\/\/ti.me\/1IQoHbt\"><param name=\"includeAPI\" value=\"true\"><param name=\"templateLoadHandler\" value=\"Time.application.brightcoveFacade._onTemplateLoad\"><param name=\"templateReadyHandler\" value=\"Time.application.brightcoveFacade._onTemplateReady\"><param name=\"wmode\" value=\"opaque\"><param name=\"htmlFallback\" value=\"true\"><param name=\"@videoPlayer\" value=\"4389502505001\"><\/object><\/div>\n<p>The sailing venue in Guanabara Bay is badly polluted, as is a separate venue for rowing and canoeing &mdash; Rodrigo de Freitas lake &mdash; in central Rio. The AP investigation also showed venues for triathlon and open-water swimming off Copacabana Beach had high virus levels that pose a threat to athletes and tourists.<\/p>\n<p>Sowrey, who spoke from Kuala Lumpur, has a local interest. His wife Alesandra is a native of Rio, and he has a 9-year-old daughter Marie.<\/p>\n<p>&#8220;I&#8217;m a father myself,&#8221; Sowrey said. &#8220;I want to make sure that everyone who goes out in the water is as safe as possible and is given the right guidance and right security.&#8221;<\/p>\n<p>The AP analysis showed dangerously high levels of viruses and bacteria from sewage in venues where about 1,400 athletes will compete in water sports, in the games which open in a year &mdash; Aug. 5, 2016.<\/p>\n<p>In Rio, much of the waste and sewage goes untreated and runs down hillside ditches and streams into Olympic water venues that are littered with floating rubbish, household waste, and even dead animals.<\/p><div class=\"content-ad\" id=\"content-ad-3981194\"><\/div>\n<p>At the world swimming championships in Kazan, Russia, swimmers said they were worried about the situation in Rio.<\/p>\n<p>&#8220;The athletes and the athletes&#8217; commission have expressed their concern at the current problems with the quality of water, the cleanliness of the water,&#8221; Vladimir Salnikov, a former Olympic gold-medal winner, said. &#8220;That will be put into a recommendation, and people will pay attention to that.&#8221;<\/p>\n<p>Shin Otsuka, an executive board member of the International Triathlon Union, said on Friday his body was considering testing for viruses.<\/p>\n<p>The ITU is holding an Olympic qualifying race on Sunday using the waters off Copacabana Beach.<\/p>\n<p>Costa Rican triathlete Leonardo Chacon said he knows the risks, but will take them.<\/p>\n<p>&#8220;We know we are exposed to viruses, maybe to a health problem later,&#8221; he said on Friday in Rio. &#8220;But in my case, I have invested so much to prepare myself for this, and I want this to happen because I can&#8217;t recuperate this investment any other way other than competing and winning the points that I need to win.&#8221;<\/p>\n<p>When Rio was awarded the Olympics in 2009, it promised cleaning its waters would be an Olympic legacy. But Rio Mayor Eduardo Paes has repeatedly acknowledged this will not be done, calling it a &#8220;lost opportunity.&#8221;<\/p>\n<p>Sowrey said the ISAF would start doing its own water testing in Rio this month, no longer relying solely on Brazil&#8217;s government analysis.<\/p>\n<p>&#8220;We want to make sure we keep pressure on the organizing committee and the Brazilians to make sure they put some energy into cleaning up the bay,&#8221; Sowrey said. &#8220;My job is to make sure something actually happens and it&#8217;s not just talk, and someone is actually walking the walk.&#8221;<\/p>\n<p>Sowery said he received a call from a woman who wanted reassurance that the ISAF was giving the right guidance to her child and others competing in an Olympic sailing test event this month in Rio.<\/p>\n<p>He said a &#8220;backup plan&#8221; included sailing all the events outside Guanabara Bay in the open Atlantic. The ISAF has three courses there, and three inside the bay.<\/p>\n<p>He said it would be &#8220;&#8216;heartbreaking&#8221; to sail outside the bay and lose the postcard backdrop of Sugarloaf Mountain, which will be a focus of television coverage.<\/p>\n<p>In most Olympics, sailing is contested far from the main Olympic venues. In Rio, the sailors and rowers and canoeists get center stage &mdash; a chance to win fans and valuable sponsors.<\/p>\n<p>&#8220;We&#8217;re not going to sacrifice health for the sake of good pictures and good TV,&#8221; he said. &#8220;But the backdrop of Rio is an amazing backdrop, and will do something for the sport of sailing.&#8221;<\/p>\n","read_more":true,"section":{"name":"World","slug":"world","url":"http:\/\/time.com\/world\/","description":"The latest news and analysis from TIME's correspondents on world politics, diplomacy, conflict, culture, humanitarian disasters, religion and much more","world":true},"tag":{"name":"brazil","slug":"brazil","url":"http:\/\/time.com\/tag\/brazil\/"},"tags":"brazil","hero":{"class":"landscape","thumbnail":"https:\/\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2015\/08\/rio-beach-water.jpg?quality=65&strip=color&w=100&h=100&crop=1","src":{"small":"https:\/\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2015\/08\/rio-beach-water.jpg?quality=65&strip=color&w=280","small_2x":"https:\/\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2015\/08\/rio-beach-water.jpg?quality=65&strip=color&w=560","large":"https:\/\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2015\/08\/rio-beach-water.jpg?quality=65&strip=color&w=550","large_2x":"https:\/\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2015\/08\/rio-beach-water.jpg?quality=65&strip=color&w=1100"},"credit":"Ricardo Moraes\u2014Reuters","caption":"A fisherman casts his line as birds fly over the Sao Conrado beach in Rio de Janeiro on Feb. 26, 2015. ","alt":"rio de janeiro brazil water","providers":[],"masonry":{"small_width":300,"small_height":197,"large_width":625,"large_height":411}},"id":3981194,"encoded_url":"http%3A%2F%2Ftime.com%2F3981194%2Fvirus-sewage-olympics-rio-who%2F","encoded_shortlink":"http%3A%2F%2Fti.me%2F1IQoHbt","encoded_title":"WHO+Seeks+Virus+Tests+After+Se